public class PowerOfThree {

    public static boolean is powerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }

        // The floating-point logarithm base 3 of n (rounded to the nearest integer)
        double logN = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);

        // Rounding to the nearest integer and checking if it's an integer
        return Double.doubleToLongBits(logN) == Double.doubleToLongBits(Math.round(logN));
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27));  // Output: true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));   // Output: false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1));  // Output: false
    }
}
```

Let's break it down:

1. We first handle edge cases, such as when the input value is less than or equal to 0, in which case we return `false`.
2. We calculate the base-3 logarithm of `n` using `Math.log(n) / Math.log(3)`.
3. Since we are using floating-point arithmetic, there will be some precision loss, so we round the result to the nearest integer using `Math.round(logN)`.
4. We then convert the floating-point number back to a long integer using `Double.doubleToLongBits` and check if it is the same as the long integer obtained from rounding the floating-point logarithm. This comparison is made to ensure the exactness of the representation at the binary level.
5. If the two integer values match, `n` is a power of three; otherwise, it isn't.

